{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503615"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:04:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:04:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2050"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2050"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.77,0.11,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38495"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2050"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22920"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43113"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38495"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents with a two-month history of joint pain. Her knuckles on both hands have been swollen and stiff and are particularly worse in the mornings. It is not currently affecting her job as an assistant in an office, nor is it affecting her day to day function. She has not noticed any rashes nor any eye pain in the past. Her medical history includes being a 15 pack-year smoker and carpal tunnel release surgery on her left hand one year ago. The patient takes no regular medications and does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-nuclear antibodies","Anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide antibodies","Bilateral hand X-ray","HLA-B27 antigen","Joint aspiration for culture and microscopy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe given history is typical of rheumatoid arthritis (RA), with the characteristic insidious onset of symmetrical joint pain and swelling which are worse in the morning. The age and gender demographic is also typical of RA, and smoking is the strongest environmental risk factor for development of RA. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-cyclic citrullinated peptide antibody\u003C/strong\u003E testing is highly specific for RA, and is also associated with a higher likelihood of progression to erosive disease. \u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cbr\u003EAnti-nuclear antibody testing may be useful for excluding alternate diagnoses such as systemic lupus erythematous but would not confirm the primary suspected diagnosis. A bilateral hand X-ray may be useful as a baseline, however hand X-rays are typically normal in RA until at least three months after the onset of symptoms. The HLA-B27 antigen is strongly associated with spondyloarthropathies such as ankylosing spondylosis and reactive arthritis, but would not confirm a diagnosis of RA. A joint aspiration for microscopy and culture would be used to confirm a diagnosis of septic arthritis. Given the two-month history and the rapid clinical course of septic arthritis, this is an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide antibody testing has high specificity for the diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis"],"references":["Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. (2019). Recommendations for the diagnosis and management of early rheumatoid arthritis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22920"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2050"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22920"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-29T09:06:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-07-29T09:06:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2050"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38495"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a